[normal]&#xa0;[bold]1.1[bold] 
[normal]The basis for devolving funds and powers to local areas is to pass greater control 
[normal]over setting the vision 
[normal]and delivering growth 
[normal]and ensuring
[normal] that businesses are involved in driving the economic prosperity o
[normal]f their areas. 
[normal]This 
[normal]i
[normal]s based on 
[normal]Lord 
[normal]Heseltine's recommendations in his report ' 
[normal]No Stone unturned'
[normal] which called for the creation of a single cash pot, which could be worth up to £49bn, bringing together dispara
[normal]te funding streams from across G
[normal]overnment wit
[normal]hout ring fences. However the reality is that funding levels are expected to be closer to £2bn per annum. Most of this is 
[normal]understood to be 
[normal]recycled funding for 
[normal]L
[normal]ocal 
[normal]A
[normal]uthorities from transport, housing and skills budgets, including some 55% funding from Df
[normal]t. However this funding is to be 
[normal]unringfenced
[normal] for LEP’s to bid 
[normal]for 
[normal]on a competitive basis for a Growth Deal to help secure a share towards driving economic growth in their areas. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]1.2[bold] 
[normal]The rational is fully appreciated in that there needs to be greater 
[normal]involvement of businesses in setting the vision and helping achi
[normal]eve economic prosperity for local
[normal] areas. However there needs to be a balanced approach 
[normal]including democratically elected Members as key decision makers 
[normal]to 
[normal]tackling
[normal] the 
[normal]key challenges and ensuri
[normal]ng that the 
[normal]right conditions for growth 
[normal]ar
[normal]e achieved and sustained into the future. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]1.3[bold] 
[normal]The main advantage
[normal]s
[normal] of devolving funding 
[normal]are
[normal] that 
[normal]it is 
[normal]unringfenced
[normal] and provides 
[normal]greater certainty over levels of funding anticipated over a longer period from 2015 -202
[normal]1 (if the allocations announced in the summer of 2014 cover that period rather than simply 2015/16 levels only). 
[normal]Thi
[normal]s offers greater potential than cyclical funding bid rounds which are generally 
[normal]for specific Departmental deliverables over a very short per
[normal]iod and require a detailed business case 
[normal]up front – such as Pinch points/
[normal] Growing Places. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]1.4[bold] 
[normal]This should help areas with developing a more holistic 
[normal]programme
[normal] and pipeline of projects focused on delivering economic benefits. The advantage being that there is 
[normal]bett
[normal]er potential to deal with the myriad of complex issues and challenges that need to be a
[normal]ddressed to create and maintain the right conditions for growth. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]1.5[bold] 
[normal]On disadvantages, much of the funding has 
[normal]been top sliced from 
[normal]Authorities 
[normal]budgets
[normal], and not all is 
[normal]unringfenced
[normal]. 
[normal]Also LEP’s will be
[normal] 
[normal]the key decision makers regarding the priorities for fund
[normal]ing for their areas
[normal], and 
[normal]Authorities will 
[normal]now 
[normal]need to be able to convince LEP’s regarding priorities. 
[normal]Therefore i
[normal]n many ways the decision maki
[normal]ng powers appear to be 
[normal]removed f
[normal]r
[normal]o
[normal]m the democratically elected local 
[normal]M
[normal]embers. There is a greater 
[normal]focus on ‘busines
[normal]s’ leading on 
[normal]the priorities for their areas.
[normal] While
[normal] 
[normal]b
[normal]usiness involvement is critical in helping to inspire and innovate and 
[normal]inform
[normal] the ambitions for local areas
[normal], this should be
[normal] as part 
[normal]of an overall balanced approach led by 
[normal]democratically elected Members 
[normal]with ultimate responsibility for achieving the agreed outcomes for their communities.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]1.6[bold] 
[normal]There is also a risk 
[normal]that money will be spent on 
[normal]bidding processes and 
[normal]sp
[normal]ecific support 
[normal]iniatives
[normal] for a short period without 
[normal]necessarily addressing the 
[normal]underlying challe
[normal]nges and improving the conditions for businesses to grow and thrive
[normal] into the future
[normal].  
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]1.7[bold] 
[normal]The 
[normal]model could be improved 
[normal]if Governmen
[normal]t made the funding available to ‘
[normal]LEP area
[normal]’s’
[normal], 
[normal]rather than a specific body 
[normal]with local areas 
[normal]deciding 
[normal]which 
[normal]organsiation
[normal] was best 
[normal]placed to 
[normal]lead and 
[normal]manage the funds
[normal] as ‘Accountable Authority
[normal]’
[normal], much as the LTB arrangement works
[normal]. There are options 
[normal]for different arrangements 
[normal]which 
[normal]could include County/ Upper Tier Boards, 
[normal]LEP, 
[normal]Economic Prosperity Boards, Joint Strategic Committees or 
[normal]alternatives. The key issue is th
[normal]at local areas should ideally decide and deals should be based on 
[normal]outcomes 
[normal]to be delivered 
[normal]and funding devolved on that basis. 
[normal]Government would still set clear criteria and conditions for allocation of funds in LEP areas su
[normal]ch as requiring a strong evidence base, or operating across the LEP area or having private sector involvement
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]1.8[bold] 
[normal]It will be important to enhance t
[normal]he role of 
[normal]local Leaders/
[normal] democratically elected members 
[normal]who 
[normal]are 
[normal]the 
[normal]key decision makers mandated to deliver 
[normal]for
[normal] their communities.
[normal] 
[normal]Most of the duty lies with the local authorities given their statutory functions around 
[normal]transport and 
[normal]planning for growth and prosperity, and 
[normal]they 
[normal]are re
[normal]sponsible for delivering on these 
[normal]ambitions
[normal].  
