[normal]2.1[bold] 
[normal]There is a real lack of resources to assess, 
[normal]prioritise
[normal] and deliver local transport sche
[normal]mes across all levels currently.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]2.2[bold] 
[normal]LEP’s have been set up with minimal resources and are intended to be lean bodies with a focus on achieving through thei
[normal]r partners. However this means that the Authorities 
[normal]deliver many of the aims and 
[normal]provide revenue support for basic operation of the LEP. The 
[normal]lack of capacity and resources 
[normal]means in some case LEP’s are spread t
[normal]hin and don’t have the resource
[normal] or expertise to support on transport schemes. Indeed this is the role for the Local Transport Authorities to assess, 
[normal]prioritise
[normal] and deliver local transport schemes. However the difficulty is that Authorities budgets have been reduced significantly from 20
[normal]08 levels, where both integrated transport and maintenance budgets were reduced by almost 45%. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]2.3[bold] 
[normal]Reduced budgets, particularly on the revenue side coupled with a lack of available resource funding from Government, (apart from specific 
[normal]programmes
[normal] like LSTF 
[normal]aimed at behavioral changes which has been useful) there have not been resources to undertake early options appraisal 
[normal]or 
[normal]scheme development work. Therefore in most cases, Local Authorities 
[normal]don’t have a pipeline of projects and focus only on key projects th
[normal]ey can commit to in terms of resources 
[normal]to progress critical schemes to support growth. M
[normal]ost m
[normal]ajor projects and schemes require significant 
[normal]up front
[normal] investment and ofte
[normal]n over a lengthy period of time
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal]Examples for this area include Cambridge Science Park St
[normal]ation, which has been in the LTP for 
[normal]years
[normal], and while there was understood to be a good business case, there was never sufficient major schemes funding to progress 
[normal]the case 
[normal]to delivery. Through strong local leadership and a willingness to take the risk, 
[normal]Ca
[normal]mbridgeshire
[normal] County Council 
[normal]is progressing the case to 
[normal]approval for 
[normal]de
[normal]livery. However developing the c
[normal]ase and designing to a detailed stage has taken some 3 years and cost 
[normal]millions
[normal] to take it to planning 
[normal]approval 
[normal]stage for Network Rail to take forward to d
[normal]elivery stage. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]2.4[bold] 
[normal]Most of the current 
[normal]Government funding tends only to be available when schemes are at an advanced stage and for the most part have all their approvals in place. This means that schemes are unlikely to come forward unless the Local Authorit
[normal]ies’ have committed to progressing them. There is little funding available to test options or look for more innovative solutions, 
[normal]therefore 
[normal]Local Authorities 
[normal]have to invest significant 
[normal]in terms of 
[normal]option appraisal /
[normal]scheme development with little resources,
[normal] partic
[normal]ularly at the early stages. The LGF offers potential in terms of 
[normal]now building up a 
[normal]programme
[normal] 
[normal]and pipeline 
[normal]for delivery 
[normal]over time to hopefully address priorities
[normal].
[normal] That is provided there is agreement locally with LEP’s on priorities and funding.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]3.1[bold] 
[normal]While a focus on the functional economic area is important, 
[normal]it
[normal] would be helpful to have a more comprehensive vision and appro
[normal]ach across a wider area
[normal]. This would 
[normal]help ensure join up on approach and priorities around improving access to markets, and fostering relationships between related industries and spreading the benefits of growth
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]3.2[bold] 
[normal]Ideally there needs to be a wider overview 
[normal]to ensure clarity and consistency across LEP’s and LTB areas regarding the challenges and priorities. There is a risk that at the moment, particularly for the key corridors that there could be a lack of join up and investment to support addressing key aims
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]3.3[bold] 
[normal]Some good work was done in the past on Regional Transport Plan, and this type of overview would be particularly helpful if linked to an investment plan and join up on priorities for investment 
[normal]including 
[normal]key 
[normal]partners 
[normal]like 
[normal]Dft
[normal], Highways Agency and Network
[normal] Rail. This could also then ensure join up on cross boundary priorities for LTB’s and LEP’s. This would be particularly helpful for transport issues which are not related to specific geographies and with a greater focus on corridors and improving links and
[normal] accessibility to and between key destinations to support more efficient movement of people and goods’ 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]4.1[bold] 
[normal]There is a good working relationship at the local level between the Authorities across 
[normal]Cambridgeshire
[normal] and 
[normal]Peterborough
[normal] where the authorities are working closely under the Duty to cooperate particularly on planning and transport matters.
[normal]  As part of this wo
[normal]rk the authorities have agr
[normal]eed their objectively assessed
[normal] housing needs across the whole area and Members have worked together to develop a 
[normal]Draft 
[normal]Long Term Transport Strategy to identify the key measures and interventions needed to support growth and conti
[normal]nued economic prosperity looking forward. 
[normal]4.2[bold] 
[normal]The Greater Cambridge Greater Peterborough 
[normal]Shadow 
[normal]Local Transport Body has proven to be an effective and efficient body where the LEP and the Upper tier authorities have worked successfully to develop a robust and
[normal] deliverable major schemes programme within a challenging timescale. The Body was set up to secure devolved major schemes funding in response to 
[normal]Dft’s
[normal] request and systems were put in place to comply with requirements. Despite being awarded 33% less funding
[normal] than anticipated, the LTB agreed 6 priority schemes within a challenging timescale.  
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]4.3[bold] 
[normal]Further to this, t
[normal]he LEP has 
[normal]now 
[normal]tasked the LTB with developing a 
[normal]programme
[normal] of transport schemes to recommend to the LEP for inclusion in 
[normal]their Strategic Economic Plan 
[normal]to drive economic growth. This process is working well despite the challenging timescales. However there is some concern that while the LTB is developing a robust and deliverable 
[normal]programme
[normal] aimed at supporting and facilitating growth, it is up to the LEP to
[normal] decide on priorities and funding, and the duty will still fall to the Authorities to deliver on most of the 
[normal]ambitions
[normal] although they may not have the resources to do so.  
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]4.4[bold] 
[normal]Looking forward
[normal], it is proposed to review 
[normal]the terms of reference 
[normal]and remit 
[normal]for the LTB to align with the LEP and 
[normal]wider role and geography.
[normal]4.5[bold] 
[normal]O
[normal]ur LEP has been greatly supportive of transport as a key priority for this area and recognizes the key role this plays in everyday lives and as a key enabler of growth. Indeed our LEP is alre
[normal]ady providing some £50m towards supporting the delivery of the A14 improvement scheme and has agreed the 
[normal]Df
[normal]T
[normal] funding previously committed to major schemes which is welcome. However there is a risk that the LEP will decide that 
[normal]they
[normal] need to 
[normal]prioritise
[normal] other
[normal] area
[normal]s
[normal] 
[normal]now
[normal], without necessarily understanding that authorities won’t have resources without the LGF to progress key schemes that support and unlock growth.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]4.6[bold] 
[normal]There is a good local working relationship between the LEP, LTB and HA, and Dft. However there is a
[normal] lack of clarity regarding future expectations in relation to LGF, in terms of the 
[normal]future 
[normal]role and remit of the LTB, working cross boundaries and assessment criteria for LGF. More join up in terms of clarity on expectations for key Departments would be hel
[normal]pful 
[normal]to ensure consistency and c
[normal]ertaint
[normal]y regarding the
[normal] arrangements.
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]5.1[bold] 
[normal]The funding environment is challenging particularly 
[normal]given 
[normal]that l
[normal]evels of Integrated Block and Maintenance Block funding have been reduced by some 45% already from 2008 levels. There is uncertainty over what the 
[normal]proposed 
[normal]top slice of funding for the 
[normal]Integra
[normal]ted B
[normal]lock into the Single Local Growth
[normal] Fund pot will mean for future t
[normal]ransport funding from 2015 onwards. In addition, 
