[normal]5.4[bold] 
[normal]While a major uplift in major schemes funding 
[normal]is most welcome 
[normal]from 
[normal]Dft
[normal], it isn’t clear that this funding will be available to support the delivery of major schemes as all of
[normal] this funding is now going into the LGF. The difficulty is that the LGF is 
[normal]unringfenced
[normal] and can be spent on LEP priorities towards delivering economic benefits which can vary enormously in terms of outputs. There is also no guarantee that the LEP will see 
[normal]transport as their top priority and therefore no certainty that the funding will support priority transport projects. 
[normal]5.5[bold] 
[normal]In addition, LEP’s will be making decision
[normal]s
[normal] on priorities for the funding without necessarily understanding the local government funding 
[normal]context. There may be an assumption that 
[normal]Authorities
[normal] will carry on with 
[normal]‘
[normal]business as usual
[normal]’ and fund
[normal] schemes. However the reality 
[normal]is
[normal] that basic
[normal] budgets have been reduced and unless 
[normal]Authoritie
[normal]s
[normal] can access this LGF funding to help deliver priorities, the pro
[normal]grammes 
[normal]could well
[normal] need to be reduced
[normal] to match the reality of reduced funding
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]6.1[bold] 
[normal]Devolving funding to local areas from 
[normal]2015 to 2021 is welcome
[normal]. H
[normal]owever 
[normal]as the
[normal] funding is going 
[normal]though
[normal] the LEP, 
[normal]t
[normal]h
[normal]is
