[normal]7.3[bold] 
[normal]Providing local areas with greater freedoms and flexibilities, particularly in terms 
[normal]of
[normal] funding will enable areas to ta
[normal]ke 
[normal]more of the initiative to support the growth and prosperity of their local areas. One example that 
[normal]is providing 
[normal]successful in 
[normal]Cambridgeshire
[normal] 
[normal]i
[normal]s the creation of a Rolling Infrastructure Fund
[normal] whereby an 
[normal]initial £8 million o
[normal]f Government funding was used to establish a rolling 
[normal]fund.
[normal] This
[normal] funding was originally used to fund the Guided 
[normal]Busway
[normal] (£5.75 million) and to act as pump-priming funding for 
[normal]Addenbrookes
[normal] Access Road (£2.25 million) during the 2007-08 financial year. During 2008-09 the money was recovered from the Guided 
[normal]Busway
[normal] scheme a
[normal]nd then 
[normal]reused
[normal] to provide front-funding for the 
[normal]Addenbrookes
[normal] Access Road, therefore resulting in all £8 million being used to support spending on this project. 
[normal]The provision of this access road
[normal] help
[normal]ed
[normal] unlock up to 4,000 new homes on the Cambridge southern 
[normal]fringe 
[normal]development which otherwise would have been delayed due to 
[normal]cashflow
[normal]/ recessionary impacts.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]7.4[bold] 
[normal]In addition to this, an equity investment of £8 million 
[normal]was made to help bring forward the 
[normal]development as part of the Rolling Fund. 
[normal]T
[normal]hese investments will 
[normal]no
[normal]w 
[normal]repay with interest, or an equity return, and the funds will then be available for investments to support housing growth across Cambridgeshire in the future. 
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]8.1[bold] 
[normal]Currently the lines of accountability are clear for local decision making on transport expenditure. Most funding for transport is allocated to the Local Transport Authorities through either the Integrated Transport Block or Maintenance Block by formula, 
[normal]with some 
[normal]periodic 
[normal]competitive bids for areas like 
[normal]Pinchpioints
[normal], Growing Places, LSTF and BBAF.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]8.2[bold] 
[normal]In 
[normal]Cambridgeshire
[normal] funding is then allocated towards the range of requirements identified in the Area Transport Strategies. These have been developed working wi
[normal]th County and Local District Members and clarify the policy objectives and identify the key measures and interventions needed to address issues and support growth. This process works successfully and well, and S106 funding is also collected towards mitigat
[normal]ing the impacts of growth and supports the aims
[normal] of the strategies
[normal].  
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]8.3[bold] 
[normal]Looking forward, from 2015, while the formula grant element will remain with the Local Transport Authorities
[normal], the amount of funding is being top sliced and
[normal] there is less certainty regard
[normal]ing arrangements for local decision making on transport expenditure
[normal] for this and the major schemes funding
[normal]. 
[normal] While LTB’s have been set up to receive the devolved funding, this will now be administered by the LEP’s through the single pot. However the assess
[normal]ment criteria and decision making processes are unclear. The other issue is that democratically elected Members are not necessarily the decision makers as the LEP’s are primarily business led
[normal], and the funding will support the LEP’s priorities
[normal]. This is a co
[normal]ncern 
[normal]as 
[normal]there may not be agreement on funding for priorities which could impact 
[normal]on the potential for areas to address the key challenges in terms of transport and create the right conditions for growth.  
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]8.4[bold] 
[normal]More consideration needs to be given the 
[normal]important role of the LTB in terms of decision making on transport funding. The LTB’s have been set up with clear lines of accountability, and assurance framework
[normal]s
[normal] setting out 
[normal]clear assessment and appraisal criteria to ensure value for money and democratic
[normal] accountability. In the Greater Cambridge Greater Peterborough area discussions are taking place about aligning the LTB to better fit the LEP geography and wider remit regarding transport as there is recognition of the important role of this body in terms 
[normal]of supporting the LEP and recommending to the LEP a robust and deliverable 
[normal]programme
[normal] that addresses the challenges and delivers economic benefits.
